&gt; 
&gt; If I run three tests, I want JUnit to report 3 runs, not 1. It will 
eventually confuse someone at a key moment. It always does. It&#39;s like 
trying to remember a lie: eventually it catches up with you -- it&#39;s 
easier to tell the truth from the beginning.
&gt; 
&gt; &gt;sure you&#39;re running
&gt; &gt;multiple tests in one test method, but it is still easy to track
&gt; &gt;specific problems down since you get the stack trace.
&gt; 
&gt; True enough, but it doesn&#39;t give me an accurate picture of the 
number of tests in the system.
&gt; 
&gt; Simple solution:
&gt; 
&gt; public void testTwoIntegers() {
&gt;     // use a and b from fixture
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; public static Test suite() {
&gt;     int[][] testData = new int[][] {
&gt;         {Integer.minValue, Integer.minValue},
&gt;         {Integer.maxValue, Integer.maxValue},
&gt;         ...
&gt;     };
&gt; 
&gt;     TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();
&gt;     for (int i = 0; i &lt; testData.length; i++) {
&gt;         suite.addTest(new IntegerTest(testData[i][0], testData[i]
[1]);
&gt;     }
&gt; 
&gt;     return suite;
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; public IntegerTest(int a, int b) {
&gt;     super(&quot;testTwoIntegers&quot;);    // leverage TestCase reflection to 
run test method &#39;testTwoIntegers&#39;
&gt;     // set fixture for test
&gt;     this.a = a;
&gt;     this.b = b;
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; An alternative, with less magic, is to override runTest().
&gt; 
&gt; public void testTwoIntegers(int a, int b) {
&gt;     // test implementation
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; public static Test suite() {
&gt;     int[][] testData = new int[][] {
&gt;         {Integer.minValue, Integer.minValue},
&gt;         {Integer.maxValue, Integer.maxValue},
&gt;         ...
&gt;     };
&gt; 
&gt;     TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();
&gt;     for (int i = 0; i &lt; testData.length; i++) {
&gt;         suite.addTest(new IntegerTest() {
&gt;             protected void runTest() {
&gt;                 testTwoIntegers(testData[i][0], testData[i][1]);
&gt;             }
&gt;         });
&gt;     }
&gt; 
&gt;     return suite;
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; I prefer the first because it avoids a bunch of anonymous 
subclasses.
